#Myth and #Monster 
2) LA’s Fallen Angel forged in 2016  @adams_forge 

The angel has fallen from his shining city, to become not the tempter of Christian mythos, but the tempted. One of the cities countless thousands of homeless, whose lives are like a dark mirror to the dreams that LA symbolizes to so many.

He is clutching an empty beer can, and a begging hat, which is engraved with a certain political slogan. Neither will bring salvation. The begging hat indeed has no bottom to it - it is a vessel as empty of promise as the can in his other hand.

Todays #Myth and #Monster sculpture is a contemplative piece called “After the Fall”

Forged in my own studio this small piece is a reimagining of the tale of Icarus, from the perspective of his father Daedalus. I tried with the figure to create a sense of loss - the slump of his head and shoulders. His wings, that were supposed to fly him and his son to freedom are grounded and weighty, worn like a mantle of his grief as he stares down at the remains of his son…

Less # Myth and more #Monster.
The Alien Seed Pods.

Forged back in 2006.
Not everything is figuratively based!

This triptych was inspired by my lifelong love of sci-fi, and my move to a new continent… thereby becoming an alien myself. Thoughts on what it means to be an immigrant, meets
Day of the Triffids, meets the Xenomoroh. 

The seed pod opens to reveal a carnivorous plant form within. The apical bud echoing the form of the pod it has slithered out from, in a monstrously phoenix like state of regeneration. 

Keep your boots on out there and stay frosty!!

Today’s #Myth and #Monster is a little blend of both.
 “Nature bites back”
Forged as a collaborative one day sculpture at Bringsty Forge in the UK.

This is my interpretation of what a modern day dryad might look like, were one to be encountered in the deep woods.
With the relentless and unrepentant expansion of humanity into the farthest corners of the globe, there is little space left for the undisturbed glades where dryads may once have dreamed their days away playing harps and knitting flower crowns.

This is an angry nature spirit, all teeth and claws, ready to spring to the defence of its dwindling domain. I can’t help but feel that if nature could manifest itself in such an anthropomorphic way, this is what we would get…

#Myth and #Monster.
Nightmare creepy crawlies. 
Circa 2000, forged in Braishfield, UK while I worked for @redanvilforge.

I went full my sci-fi on this series of mutated bugs. 
These were where I think I really started to capture the sense of impending movement that has become such an important part of all my work since.
Forged steel is so alive as it is being worked, and can be crafted to maintain some of that life even once it has cooled. I really enjoy creating an impression of potential motion - at first impressions, or glimpsed from the corner of your eye these creatures really feel as if they are about to come for you…

Springtime #Myth and #Monster. The sun is shining here, the birds are doing their thing…

A light dabble with the Nordic legends. This was my interpretation of Freyja, the goddess of fertility.
The body and head are forged from a single piece of steel, she stands about 3’ tall.

I wanted to capture a sort of graceful flowing motion for this sculpture. All soft lines and sensual curves. 
#NotAlwaysSpiky

Friday #Myth and #Monster feels.
Gargoyles/Demons

My take on one of my favourite of all architectural features. From oogly carved figures on medieval buildings to free and freaky independant and possibly a bit naughty creatures.
 
This one was forged a couple of weekends ago at the @ca_blacksmith_association conference. 

Entitled “Not all lights will lead you safely home” this is a very demonically influenced gargoyle, holding a lantern aloft to lead you astray… you the viewer can decide what temptation that lantern represents.

The way the figurine is holding onto the post gives it a sense of intent and movement. It has just alighted there, and is perched, ready to spring aloft at any moment.

Fantastic work from many hands to out this one together! 

#BuildingsNeedGargoyles

#Myth and #Monster for the weekend.
Personal mythology. 

If you know me you have probably realized I don’t really consider being a blacksmith to be a job so much as an all defining aspect of  who I am. 

I am not religious, but if I was to lay my prayers at an alter it would be before an anvil.

This collaborative sculpture forged @centerformetalarts translates my sense of awe and wonder about this thing I get to do every day into a quasi mythological figure. My personal god. 
#TheBlacksmith

“Paddle Deconstructed” 
Collaboration with Nu-chan-nulth master carver @moysutherland.

 The following words are from our Artist statement about the piece:

Cedar and Iron are the materials that formed the backbones of two 
great civilizations. They are worked into every aspect of the lives of the 
respective inhabitants of these two worlds. These were materials not 
only of utilitarian necessity, but of the expression of art, beauty and culture. Yet, their meeting on the west coast of the ‘new wold’ was one 
that heralded the beginning of a conflicting, violent  and traumatic period of history, one that we are still living with today.
That meeting of cultures, of materials brought about the wholesale destruction of one of those civilizations. The legacy of iron here in North America is one of pain and loss to the indigenous inhabitants of this continent.
This collaboration brings 
together these two opposing materials in a way that has not been 
done before. We combine the narrative traditions of the Nuu-chah-nulth First nation with the structural possibilities of forged iron, 
seeking to re-interpret old stories, and begining to tell new ones. The 
strength of iron, once used to destroy, is here harnessed to carry the 
cedar forms, giving us a freedom to create expressive works of art that would be impossible in either Iron or Cedar alone.
Both artists have a desire to take an unflinching look at the history of 
their own people, of contact and its ramifications, and their work will reflect the darker side of the foundation of a European America, whilst also expressing a beauty and desire for a future in which we can hope to regain some balance. 

The paddle is a symbol of the journey, of navigation, of control over your destination. Here though the paddle is cut apart, symbolic of the effects of colonialism, the shattering of the journey. We then present it again, deconstructed and reconstructed. Still a paddle in shape, still beautiful, but with a totally new and redefined purpose, and each needs to other to continue on this new path….

#Myth and #Monster
The Gloomstalker
Collaboration with master carver @moysutherland 

A modern representation of a traditional 1st nations tale of the blue heron. The figure is transitioning between its animal and human form: A fearsome creature looming out of the west coast fog.

I love this piece, capturing the awe inspiring roots of so much mythology, the narrative traditions woven into our interpretation of the world around us, how they have informed the artistic traditions of people and place, and then being able to retell those stories with different materials and between different people.

My approach to sculptural iron is so far removed from the west coast indigenous style of carving, yet we can make them work so well together, and I loved delving into the darker side of the 1st nations mythology with Moy.
Cedar and Iron. 
🔥🔥🔥
